MiFID
MiFID (The Markets in Financial Instruments Directive) is an EU regulation that came into force on November 1, 2007. The Directive sets out requirements for the entire European financial sector in order to create a single market for financial instruments. Its main task is to promote the development of an effective, transparent and integrated trade and financial infrastructure, including providing a high level of protection for investors. The Directive contains measures aimed at changing and improving the work of investment companies, promoting the development of international trade, and creating strategic opportunities. The full text of the Directive can be found on the website.
As an investment company regulated by the EU, EXANTE is also subject to the MiFID. To fully comply with the requirements of the Directive, EXANTE has implemented all the necessary documentation, procedures and regulations. EXANTE actively supports partners' compliance with the Directive by providing them with a wide range of services that help partners meet local requirements of the Directive and hence lead to lower costs.
The Malta Financial Services Authority monitors the compliance of Maltese investment companies with the requirements of the Directive.
Client classification: test suitability and appropriateness
MiFID requires companies to classify clients in three main categories: "Eligible Counterparties", "Professional Clients", and "Retail Clients " (clients of the latter category have the highest level of protection) and assess their appropriateness for the offered products.
Post-trade transparency
EXANTE guarantees transparency of transactions in accordance with the requirements of the MiFID. In order to enable investors or market participants to have access to the terms of potential transactions on the stock market at any time, and to subsequently verify the terms on which transactions were made, EXANTE publishes information about completed stock transactions and discloses information about the current opportunities in the market. More specifically, all types of transactions with financial instruments made on regulated markets, stock exchange or OTC markets are subject to compelling disclosure.
Best order execution
The MiFID requires investment companies to take all possible measures to achieve the best possible result in executing clients' orders. However, the best possible result is not limited to the order execution price, but also includes other factors, such as the speed and likelihood of order execution, and the likelihood of payment.
EXANTE's Best Execution Policy makes the process and results transparent to the clients by: (i) using state-of-the-art routing, monitoring and execution technology; (ii) careful consideration of the details of the process; (iii) regular and detailed quality analysis.
Transaction reporting
EXANTE is required to report all transactions to the Malta Financial Services Authority.
European licenses
EXANTE is licensed to provide investment services by two European regulators: the Malta Financial Services Authority (MFSA) – license No. IS/52182, and the Cyprus Securities and Exchange Commission (CySEC) – license No. 165/12.
EXANTE is also authorized by the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) to provide services in the UK under license No.620980.
State insurance of accounts
EXANTE clients who open an account within Cyprus jurisdiction get state insurance of their funds in the amount of up to 20,000 euros.
